# Google C++ Style Guide — Cursor Rule

Apply these rules whenever you edit a C++ source or header file.

## Formatting

- 2-space indent, 80-column lines, K&R braces.
- `clang-format` with `BasedOnStyle: Google` is the source of truth — run it before saving. `.clang-format` is in the repo root.

## Naming

| Kind | Convention |
|------|------------|
| Files | `snake_case.cc` / `.h` |
| Types (class/struct/enum/alias) | `PascalCase` |
| Functions | `PascalCase` |
| Variables / parameters / locals | `snake_case` |
| Private/protected class members | `snake_case_` (trailing underscore) |
| Struct data members | `snake_case` (no trailing underscore) |
| Constants (`constexpr` / `const` at namespace/class scope) | `kCamelCase` |
| Enumerators | `kCamelCase` |
| Macros | `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` (avoid when possible) |
| Namespaces | `snake_case` |

## Includes

Group in this order, one group per block, alphabetized within each group:

1. Related header (for `foo.cc`, `foo.h`)
2. C system headers (`<sys/types.h>`)
3. C++ standard library (`<vector>`)
4. Other libraries
5. Project headers (`"project/foo/bar.h"`)

Include guard: `<PATH>_<FILE>_H_` (uppercase).

## Language Features

- `nullptr`, never `NULL` or `0`.
- `std::unique_ptr` for unique ownership. `std::shared_ptr` only when shared ownership is essential.
- Single-arg constructors must be `explicit`.
- `override` / `final` on virtual methods.
- Use `= default` / `= delete` explicitly; follow Rule of 3/5/0 consistently.
- No `using namespace std;` at namespace or global scope in headers.

## Comments

- Public classes and functions have `//` comments describing behavior, ownership, thread-safety.
- Preconditions / postconditions stated explicitly when non-obvious.

Canonical source: https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html
